Phase 3: Pro-Grade Charting (TradingView Integration)
Goal: Move away from static images to interactive, real-time TradingView charts.

The "WebView Bridge":
Develop a custom 
TradingViewChart
 component using react-native-webview.
This host a lightweight HTML envelope containing the TradingView Advanced Charting Library.
Porting the Datafeed:
Implement a Communication Bridge: The WebView will request data via postMessage, and the React Native layer will fetch it using the apiClient and send it back.
Adopt the 
tradingview-datafeed.ts
 logic for handling 
getBars
 and 
resolveSymbol
 within the mobile context.
Theme Alignment:
Apply the TIWI Brand Palette (Glassmorphism, Dark Mode tokens) directly to the TradingView overrides so it feels native to the app.
Phase 4: Optimization & Smart Fallbacks
Goal: Ensure the app stays performant even for small-cap tokens on slow networks.

Resolution Caching:
Save user preferences (e.g.,
"1H" vs "1D") in the marketStore to persist timeframe choices across symbols.
The Cross-Chain Resolve:
Ensure calls to the chart API include baseChainId and quoteChainId. This activates the backend's "Cross-Chain Calculator" for tokens that only have WBNB/WETH pairs.
Loading & Error States:
Implement "Shimmer" skeletons for the chart area while the WebView is initializing.
Add a "No Data Found" fallback if the dispatcher exhausts all providers (Binance -> dYdX -> DexScreener).
Antigravity Analysis: Why this works
Decoupled Complexity: By letting the backend handle the "Provider War" (Binance vs dYdX), the mobile app code remains clean and easy to maintain.
Zero-Latency Perception: By using 
the Zustand Bridge (implemented in the previous task) alongside this real-time data, the page looks full immediately, and only the "deep data" (orderbook/chart) populates a second later.
Institutional Quality: Using TradingView (via WebView) is the industry standard. It gives our users toolsets like MACD, RSI, and Volume profiles that are impossible to build with standard mobile chart libraries.
